[2] New drugs

ZMapp post-exposure antiserum

-----
29 Aug 2014: (BBC) The only clinical trial data on the experimental EVD [Ebola virus disease] drug ZMapp shows it is 100 percent effective in monkey studies [with 18 monkeys], even in later stages of the infection.

The researchers, publishing their data in [the journal] Nature, said it was a "very important step forward". Yet the limited supplies will not help the 20 000 people predicted to be infected during the outbreak in West Africa. And 2/7 people given the drug, have later died from EVD.... This included animals given the drug up to 5 days after infection. For the monkeys this would be a relatively late stage in the infection, around 3 days before it becomes fatal ... [more]
http://www.bbc.com/news/health-28980153

BioCryst post-exposure antiviral
---------------------------
29 Aug 2014: BioCryst Pharmaceuticals, Inc. announced this morning that their small-molecule, nucleoside analogue, BCX-4430, would be entering a dose ranging efficacy study in non-human primates within the next few weeks.... So, unlike with a vaccine, BCX-4430 is being developed as a post-exposure measure for those in environments where conditions are conducive to accidental viral exposure ... [more]
http://www.forbes.com/sites/davidkroll/2014/08/29/biocryst-to-launch-nhp-ebola-drug-safety-studies-within-weeks
[First priority would be health workers and lab workers. - Mod.JW]

NIH/GlaxoSmithKline vaccine tests to start
------------------------------------------
Federal researchers next week will start testing humans with an experimental vaccine to prevent the deadly ebolavirus.

The National Institutes of Health announced Thursday [28 Aug 2014] that it is launching the safety trial on a vaccine developed by the agency's National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases and GlaxoSmithKline. Beginning Tuesday [2 Sep 2014], it will test 20 healthy adult volunteers to see if the virus is safe and triggers an adequate response in their immune systems.

This isn't a treatment for the disease, but a hoped-for preventative measure. Fauci said the vaccine cannot cause EVD in the volunteers being tested. He cautioned that there is no guarantee it will work: "I have been fooled enough in my many years of experience."

The US vaccine takes a single protein from the ebolavirus and pairs it with a chimpanzee cold virus to help as a delivery system. Past vaccines have the used the same protein but different delivery systems.

Usually, the 2nd stage of drug trials involve testing on larger numbers of people before it goes into final testing.

A British consortium has pledged USD 4.6 million to help speed up the vaccine tests. With some of that money, GlaxoSmithKline will be able to begin manufacturing up to 10 000 doses of the US vaccine, if the tests are successful. The 10 000 doses will be ready by the end of the year [2014] and if needed, production can be ramped up for stockpiling, GSK spokeswoman Sarah Alspach said.

Fauci doesn't expect results from this initial round of testing until the end of the year....

The major target of the vaccine, if it works, would be health care workers ... [more]
http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/u-s-to-begin-safety-testing-ebola-vaccine-next-week/article_ea70492f-6f8b-5b6e-af56-44e8d591baa6.html

