[4] Sierra Leone: working in a triage tent
Date: 26 Aug 2014 [updated 27 Aug 2014]
Source: Stuff, New Zealand [edited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/world/africa/60882592/Kiwi-nurses-on-Ebola-front-line-in-Sierra-Leone


New Zealand Red Cross nurses fighting the EVD outbreak in Sierra Leone are unable to work inside the hospital where they are based because it is too dangerous. "21 of its medical staff have died and the staff who do turn up to work are scared, depressed and tired," health co-ordinator Sharon Mackie from Wellington, 45, said in a blog. She and mother of 4 Donna Collins, 48, from Whangarei recently arrived in Kenema, the worst-hit area of Sierra Leone. They are part of a multinational Red Cross team that opened 2 triage tents outside the Kenema Government Hospital.

"The local staff are traumatised," Mackie said. "This is a hospital that has lost most of its senior staff to ebolavirus due to poor understanding of isolation techniques." The goal of the triage tents was to help support patient flow and identification of suspected EVD cases, ensuring the hospital received the right patients at the right time, providing reassurance and confidence for local staff ... [more]

