[5] Ebolavirus: genomic studies
Date: Fri 29 Aug 2014
Source: IFL Science [edited]
http://www.iflscience.com/health-and-medicine/ebola-claims-lives-five-study-co-authors-paper-published


Unfortunately, before the paper "Genomic surveillance elucidates ebolavirus origin and transmission during the 2014 outbreak" could be published online yesterday [28 Aug 2014], 5 of the 50 co-authors fell ill and died from the Ebola virus disease (EVD) raging on in West Africa.
[See first page in memoriam http://nextgenseek.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/EBOLA-Genomics-in-memoriam.jpg. - Mod.JW

In the paper, the researchers sequenced the genomes of the ebolavirus from 78 patients across the affected region, including Guinea, Liberia, Sierra Leone, and Nigeria. They identified the incredibly rapid mutation rate within the virus, which is currently changing twice as fast as ever before. They were able to determine that although the virus was originally transmitted to humans through an animal reservoir, the spread has been due to human interaction with infected individuals and not by several animals infecting humans in several locations.

The co-authors who had died from EVD all had ties to Kenema Government Hospital (KGH)'s Lassa fever ward in Sierra Leone. Since the start of the outbreak, over 24 KGH personnel have died because of the EVD. Lassa is similar to EVD in that they are both acute hemorrhagic fevers with similar symptoms, though the viruses are not related ... [more]

[Byline: Lisa Winter]

